lutionary tracks with a mass\naccretion rate of $5\\times10^{-6} M_\\odot/{\\rm yr}$ and fraction of injected\naccretion energy of $\\beta=0.1$ provide the best results in enveloping the\nspectroscopic parameters of pre-main sequence stars in a constant accretion\nscenario. The calculated instability regions constrain the atmospheric boundary\nconditions to Eddington Gray atmospheres; we discuss the future potential for\nadditional constraints by instability regions that are dependent on radial\norder. We present a possible candidate for pulsations in M-type young stellar\nobjects.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Jul 2021 19:01:15 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-10-13"}
{"id":"2107.07569","submitter":"Joris Hermans","authors":"Joris Hermans and Rony Keppens","title":"Effect of optically thin cooling curves on condensation formation: Case\n  study using thermal instability","comments":"20 pages, 21 figures, accepted for publication, corrections by\n  language editor and improved quality of figures","journal-ref":"A&A 655, A36 (2021)","doi":"10.1051/0004-6361/202140665","report-no":null,"categories":"astro-ph.SR","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Non-gravitationally induced condensations are observed in many astrophysical\nenvironments. Such structures are formed due to energy loss by optically thin\nradiative emission. Instead of solving the full radiative transfer equations,\nprecomputed cooling curves are typically used in numerical simulations. In the\nliterature, there exists a wide variety of cooling curves and they are quite\noften used as unquestionable ingredients. We determine the effect of the\noptically thin cooling curves on the formation and evolution of condensations.\nWe perform a case study using thermal instability as a mechanism to form in\nsitu condensations. We compare 2D numerical simulations with different cooling\ncurves using interacting slow magnetohydrodynamic (MHD) waves as trigger for\nthe thermal instability. Furthermore, we discuss a bootstrap measure to\ninvestigate the far non-linear regime of thermal instability. In the appendix,\nwe include the details of all cooling curves implemented in MPI-AMRVAC and\nbriefly discuss a hydrodynamic variant of the slow MHD waves setup for thermal\ninstability. For all tested cooling curves, condensations are formed. However,\nthe growth rates of the thermal instability are different. Also, the morphology\nof the formed condensation widely varies. We find fragmentation that is\naffected by the low-temperature treatment of the cooling curves. Condensations\nformed using cooling curves that vanish for temperatures lower than 20 000 K\nseem to be more stable against dynamical instabilities. The non-linear regime\nand fragmentation in the hydrodynamic case differ greatly from the MHD case. We\nadvocate the use of modern cooling curves, based on accurate computations and\nup-to-date atomic parameters and solar abundances. Our bootstrap procedure can\nbe used in future multi-dimensional simulations, to study fine-structure\ndynamics in solar prominences.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 15 Jul 2021 19:02:11 GMT"},{"version":"v2","created":"Mon, 2 Aug 2021 08:24:42 GMT"}],"update_date":"2021-11-10"}
